Based on the knowledge base findings, chain-of-thought reasoning is a critical component of the ReAct framework. By incorporating reasoning traces, models are able to generate human-like, task-solving trajectories 
that are significantly more interpretable than baselines that lack such reasoning.

This approach has demonstrated strong empirical performance on interactive decision-making benchmarks, such as ALFWorld and WebShop. In these environments, the ReAct method outperformed traditional imitation and 
reinforcement learning approaches by absolute success rates of 34% and 10%, respectively, even when prompted with only one or two in-context examples.
